<span id="freeTextContainer9127841901927985035">Language in service of ideology, the danger of metaphor, the struggle to expose the material truth behind the veils of capitalist society. All the vintage Sontag topics are here, and all of them are fantastic. A short book with a punch that should give pause not only to anyone discussing the nature of disease, but also the reading public in general-- how easy it is to fall prey to our own stories about the world.<br/><br/>The comments on AIDS are especially trenchant, and, unlike many books of critical th</span>
  <span id="freeText9127841901927985035" style="display:none">Language in service of ideology, the danger of metaphor, the struggle to expose the material truth behind the veils of capitalist society. All the vintage Sontag topics are here, and all of them are fantastic. A short book with a punch that should give pause not only to anyone discussing the nature of disease, but also the reading public in general-- how easy it is to fall prey to our own stories about the world.<br /><br />The comments on AIDS are especially trenchant, and, unlike many books of critical theory and essayistic nonfiction, this one actually had a very real impact on policy and discourse, and for that alone, it should be read.</span>
