<div id="review_3741620816" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3741620816" />
    <a title="Ilse van der Spoel" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/3053696-ilse-van-der-spoel"><img alt="Ilse van der Spoel" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1468192920p2/3053696.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3741620816?book_show_action=true">Feb 16, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ilse van der Spoel" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ilse van der Spoel" href="/user/show/3053696-ilse-van-der-spoel">Ilse van der Spoel</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback " href="/book/show/29924103-illness-as-metaphor-aids-and-its-metaphors">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3053696-ilse-van-der-spoel?shelf=literature-of-grief-and-mourning">literature-of-grief-and-mourning</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3053696-ilse-van-der-spoel?shelf=theory-and-cultural-analysis">theory-and-cultural-analysis</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/3053696-ilse-van-der-spoel?shelf=to-read-finish-in-2021">to-read-finish-in-2021</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3741620816" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14703055170175406299">Some of Sontag&apos;s arguments are a bit repetitive and drawn out over the chapters, but a lot of her analyses are insightful, particularly on how language/metaphors around disease are stigmatising and entail victim blaming. Some insights are even baffling from a historical / ethical standpoint, such as that cancer patients&apos; families, and not the patients themselves were often informed of the diagnosis. At other moments she is a bit too critical / discursive, and could have also explored how some of</span>
  <span id="freeText14703055170175406299" style="display:none">Some of Sontag's arguments are a bit repetitive and drawn out over the chapters, but a lot of her analyses are insightful, particularly on how language/metaphors around disease are stigmatising and entail victim blaming. Some insights are even baffling from a historical / ethical standpoint, such as that cancer patients' families, and not the patients themselves were often informed of the diagnosis. At other moments she is a bit too critical / discursive, and could have also explored how some of the metaphors surrounding illnesses perhaps are the only way to grasp something otherwise incomprehensible or unattainable; not in the least for some patients themselves.<br /><br />An interesting read during a pandemic and a lot of her arguments still hold up today, for both the diseases she discusses (particularly cancer), as well as for COVID. She also provides many interesting literary references to explore further. I can definitely see how one would take these essays as a starting point for more (up to date) in depth critical / cultural analysis.</span>
  <a data-text-id="14703055170175406299" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


