        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4071362485" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3372308520544739771">I’m not sure when I started this book. I quit listening to it several times before I finally just pushed through it. It’s somewhat tedious and dry, and a bit dated. It is also hard to hear at times and depressing. <br/><br/>At the same time, much of it is relevant, especially to the current pandemic: the politicization of the disease, the obsession with pinpointing its foreign origination, and the prioritization of Americans and Europeans over the unfortunates who live in the rest of the world. The more t</span>
  <span id="freeText3372308520544739771" style="display:none">I’m not sure when I started this book. I quit listening to it several times before I finally just pushed through it. It’s somewhat tedious and dry, and a bit dated. It is also hard to hear at times and depressing. <br /><br />At the same time, much of it is relevant, especially to the current pandemic: the politicization of the disease, the obsession with pinpointing its foreign origination, and the prioritization of Americans and Europeans over the unfortunates who live in the rest of the world. The more things change the more they stay the same. It was always this way and one suspects it always will be. <br /><br />Diseases bring out the worst in us, whether it’s cancer, AIDS or a pandemic. If we can point out the moral failings of those who succumb (e.g., smoking, drinking, obesity, homosexuality) we can relieve our own fears. If we devalue life in other countries we need not feel bad about saving ourselves while leaving others to suffer. And even better if we can posit blame for the disease itself on those others and ways of life that we sneer at and would never practice ourselves. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3372308520544739771" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


