<div id="review_24488285" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/24488285" />
    <a title="Cher" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/1234691-cher"><img alt="Cher" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1491541837p2/1234691.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/24488285?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2008</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Cher" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Cher" href="/user/show/1234691-cher">Cher</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780312420130" href="/book/show/52375.Illness_as_Metaphor_and_AIDS_and_Its_Metaphors">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/1234691-cher?shelf=nonfiction">nonfiction</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer24488285" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15055963620572711966">Sontag does the world a wonderful favor and reminds it that illness can be just a malfunction of the body. When faced with her own cancer struggle, she discovers via the reactions of others, that much spiritual or psychological weakness is projected onto her by others. The mind/body connection, she argues, is not a thing to ignore, but it is important to be able to extricate a person&apos;s illness from their character, to examine the cultural metaphors the illness signifies to the populace. Her foll</span>
  <span id="freeText15055963620572711966" style="display:none">Sontag does the world a wonderful favor and reminds it that illness can be just a malfunction of the body. When faced with her own cancer struggle, she discovers via the reactions of others, that much spiritual or psychological weakness is projected onto her by others. The mind/body connection, she argues, is not a thing to ignore, but it is important to be able to extricate a person's illness from their character, to examine the cultural metaphors the illness signifies to the populace. Her follow up piece about AIDS is similarly insightful and definitely worth reading about.<br /><br />[Recently, my GF who suffers from spinal damage, was recommend Louise Hay's You Can Heal Your Life, which is a book of affirmations that asserts we make ourselves ill with our character flaws. This is the 18th C concept of "degenerateness" alive and flourishing. The author goes so far as to link various genetic and viral diseases with specific personality traits/flaws. I find this really obnoxious and of the "blame the victim" school of New Age faux spirituality. Germ theory, people? Accidents happen? Let's treat the actual diseases rather than punish or blame their victims!]<br /><br />What I really like about Sontag's book is that she takes what could be a memoir and turns a scholarly eye to it. So in essense this is a researched critique of how her illness caused her to be suddenly perceived differently. An excellent book for anyone facing challenging physical issues. They're hard enough to deal with without others projecting their cultural baggage onto you!<br /><br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="15055963620572711966" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


