<div id="review_1666315235" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1666315235" />
    <a title="Amanda Landegren" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/16276761-amanda-landegren"><img alt="Amanda Landegren" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1490655666p2/16276761.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1666315235?book_show_action=true">Jun 12, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Amanda Landegren" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Amanda Landegren" href="/user/show/16276761-amanda-landegren">Amanda Landegren</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1666315235" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer15819313729659050203">I do not read a lot of non-fiction so I don&apos;t really have much to compare this with. However, in the two essays Sontag presents some really interesting ideas and revealed some approaches to things that I had not really considered before. <br/><br/><b>Illness as Metaphor</b><br/>I liked this essay a lot. Unfortunately I felt like I did not know enough about tuberculosis and its history to fully appreciate those discussions. On the other hand, I found the parts elaborating on cancer and its metaphors to be very interes</span>
  <span id="freeText15819313729659050203" style="display:none">I do not read a lot of non-fiction so I don't really have much to compare this with. However, in the two essays Sontag presents some really interesting ideas and revealed some approaches to things that I had not really considered before. <br /><br /><b>Illness as Metaphor</b><br />I liked this essay a lot. Unfortunately I felt like I did not know enough about tuberculosis and its history to fully appreciate those discussions. On the other hand, I found the parts elaborating on cancer and its metaphors to be very interesting. While I might not agree with everything Sontag says, I think that she helped open my eyes for how our everyday language can affect people around us and create prejudice.<br /><br /><b>AIDS and Its Metaphors</b><br />Although I liked the first essay better, this one was still really interesting and well crafted. It did feel a bit less 'eye-opening' but that might be because we are better informed about AIDS today. (At least in Sweden). However, the effects of AIDS on our language and how that in turn affects our approaches to things proved a very thought-provoking discussion.<br /><br />Overall I found the two essays to be very interesting and I do want to try to read more non-fiction in the future. </span>
  <a data-text-id="15819313729659050203" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


