<div id="review_1119887297" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1119887297" />
    <a title="Mia" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/6519317-mia"><img alt="Mia" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1422175550p2/6519317.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1119887297?book_show_action=true">Dec 01, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Mia" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Mia" href="/user/show/6519317-mia">Mia</a>
      </span>

          added it


          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140124279" href="/book/show/2888669-illness-as-metaphor-and-aids-and-its-metaphors">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/6519317-mia?shelf=purchased">purchased</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1119887297" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer17304135419589819170">These essays had a couple of interesting points, but it didn&apos;t feel like they progressed in any logical order. Sontag&apos;s ideas are presented in what felt to me like an unstructured manner, and this lessened some of the impact of the ideas. Perhaps if I had read either of these essays at the time when they were written, back when there was more mysticism and prejudice surrounding cancer and AIDS (not that there is none now, there was just more in the &apos;80s) these essays would have been more impactf</span>
  <span id="freeText17304135419589819170" style="display:none">These essays had a couple of interesting points, but it didn't feel like they progressed in any logical order. Sontag's ideas are presented in what felt to me like an unstructured manner, and this lessened some of the impact of the ideas. Perhaps if I had read either of these essays at the time when they were written, back when there was more mysticism and prejudice surrounding cancer and AIDS (not that there is none now, there was just more in the '80s) these essays would have been more impactful. As it was, I wasn't presented with many new ideas, and the ideas that were there seemed to be repeated regularly, with not much added with each repetition.</span>
  <a data-text-id="17304135419589819170" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


